What the Artist Claims: The Originals Section of Banksy Explained and the Taxonomy of a Settlement
The originals section of Banksy Explained is the site's most carefully constructed architecture. Where the paper prints section is a ledger and the canvas editions section is a bounded catalogue, the originals section is something closer to a legal document: a precise enumeration of what the artist claims as singular objects, drawn to exclude what she does not claim, with the exclusions as forensically significant as the inclusions.
The Barely Legal separation is where the taxonomy's operating logic becomes most explicit.
The site's treatment of the 2006 Los Angeles show opens with paintings of six images that subsequently became the LA print set: Applause, Festival, Grannies, Morons, Trolleys, and Sale Ends. The text reads: "Banksy exhibited the originals for each print at Barely Legal." Then a structural break. A secondary header — "ORIGINALS EXHIBITED" — and the catalogue restarts: Picnic, Waterfall, Girl with Film Crew, and others.
The question the layout forces is simple. If the six print-set canvases were already shown as originals, why are they excluded from the definitive, unhedged inventory of originals exhibited?
The answer is visible in the single wide-angle photograph immediately preceding the Originals Exhibited section. The shot of Sale Ends Today clearly shows two canvases installed side by side on the same gallery wall: Sale Ends on the right, and Picnic directly to its left. In the physical gallery, they were neighbors. In the digital architecture of Banksy Explained, they are taxonomically ripped apart. Sale Ends stays quarantined in the commercial print-set category. Picnic is extracted and placed under the ORIGINALS EXHIBITED banner.
Physical presence at the show does not determine which column a work goes into. Something else does. The six print-set canvases, despite their status as physical paintings, belonged to a different category of object from the beginning — one the site refuses to dignify with the unhedged designation. They were the first major salvo in an aggressive strategy to convert the artist's output into liquid commodities. The originals section excludes them because the artist excludes them.

The 2005 unique is the site's clearest positive claim.
In the same year whose canvas editions it records, the originals section of Banksy Explained records a hand-painted work — an oil-painted bouquet — that is described in terms consistent with direct manual production by a trained painter. It is the one object in the entire originals record whose description aligns with a trompe l'oeil practice: the deliberate construction of a painted surface that presents as something other than what it is.
That work is not a stencil piece. It is not a spray work. It is a painting in the traditional sense, produced by someone with the training to make paint behave. Its presence in the originals section — and the absence of any equivalent description for any other work in the catalogue — is the artist placing a marker. The 2005 oil-painted bouquet is the singular confirmation of the artist's hand in a record otherwise dominated by works documented by a studio photographer whose function was commercial rather than artistic.

The Devolved Parliament footnote is the originals section's most significant omission.
The site's inventory of the 2009 Banksy vs Bristol Museum show does not include the monumental chimpanzee-parliament canvas shown under the title Question Time. The omission is precise: it reflects insider knowledge of what the object was and was not at the time of the show.
The 2009 canvas originated as a super-sized giclee print on canvas, struck from a smaller painting and comprehensively overpainted by the production department as a room-filling exhibition prop. The site excludes it because in 2009 it did not meet the criteria of an original work by the singular artist. It was production output dressed as a singular object — which is the definition of what the originals section's taxonomy is designed to exclude.
A decade later, a comprehensively reworked version of the image appeared as Devolved Parliament and sold at Sotheby's for nearly £10 million. The site had registered the distinction between the 2009 exhibition prop and the reworked singular object before the sale. The ledger was ahead of the auction house by ten years.
What the Devolved Parliament case illuminates is the originals section's operating threshold: an object does not qualify for inclusion by virtue of physical uniqueness or exhibition prominence. It qualifies by virtue of the artist's direct hand and the artist's willingness to certify it. The 2009 Question Time canvas did not meet that threshold. The 2019 Devolved Parliament canvas, comprehensively reworked, apparently did — which is why its sale record exists and why Sotheby's was willing to offer provenance guarantees for it.
The originals section is the artist's certification record. Its exclusions are as deliberate as its inclusions. Together they constitute the full claim: what she made, what she authorised, and what she refused to certify as her own regardless of whose name it sold under.

The Napalm box set sits at the intersection of the originals claim and the corporate record.
The third run of the Napalm print was included in a box set jointly produced by Damien Hirst's Other Criteria company to commemorate the Serpentine Gallery's 2006–07 show In the Darkest Hour There May Be Light: Works from Damien Hirst's Murderme Collection. This third run carried a unique modification: physical blood splatter, applied by hand to that print alone, distinguishing it from its two prior runs not only by its morbid addition but by its distinct production methodology — archival inkjet on photographic paper rather than silk screen.
The Napalm/Serpentine box set contained 50 prints with 29 APs. The standard baseline structure — 22 APs per allocation unit — does not resolve cleanly into 29. What does resolve cleanly is this: 29 equals 50 minus 21, or equivalently, the total edition minus one allocation unit minus the artist's own copy. Alternatively, 29 is the number that results when the Artist of Record is excluded from the AP allocation entirely and the artist retains her own copy plus one baseline unit for the production record.
The Napalm/Serpentine 29 is the artist encoding Hirst's exclusion from her AP allocation in the edition arithmetic of a print she defaced with blood before handing to his corporate vehicle. The blood on the print and the number of APs are the same statement made in two different registers: one physical, one numerical. The originals section of Banksy Explained records what the artist claims. The Napalm/Serpentine box set records what she was settling when she made that claim.

